Inside Britain’s grumpiest café
The Temporary Measure in Keswick is the Lake District tea room where grumbles about service have reopened the North-South divide
Eccentric outpost: William Langley inside the Temporary Measure tea room, Keswick
Photo: NORTH NEWS & PICTURES	By William Langley
9:55PM GMT 09 Nov 2013
Comments
Beyond the sound of cakes hitting crockery and the bronchial wheezings of the coffee machine, a wounded hush prevailed yesterday in the café branded the bolshiest in Britain.
Proprietor Emma Smalley shuffled around her ancient premises, plumping up the cushions, making sure the teddy bears were comfortable, commiserating with her affronted mum and occasionally attending to the customers.
Outside, sheets of greasy rain lashed the Lake District, but there was no refuge here from the awkward question Ms Smalley’s modest establishment had raised: are Northerners grumpy?
It came to the fore last week after visitors to Keswick complained on a travel website about “unwelcoming” service at the Temporary Measure tea shop in the town and declared that, despite its indisputable good points: “we won’t be coming back”.
Ms Smalley, 33, posted a tart rebuttal, pointing out that her business was located in the North: “a place that still maintains a healthy respect for a good old-fashioned surly disposition. We enjoy a good curmudgeon.”
