In a further swipe, she wrote: “November is the month when we operate a strict mean-and-surly-to-everyone policy. We have to balance out the karma, what with all the smiling we have to do in the other months.”
The backfire could be heard across the land. Wasn’t such stereotyping supposed to have died out with whippet jokes? Wasn’t the North in enough of a fix without having its hard-won reputation for hospitality questioned? Soon the true culprit emerged in the shape of Emma’s musician brother, John, 24, who helps at the café while pursuing a career as the banjo-playing frontman of an outfit called Sycamore Sykes. “John likes to work on his songs while he’s here,” said Emma, “and if he has to serve someone, it interrupts his creative processes – that’s why he may not look very happy. He doesn’t mean any harm, he’s just not very smiley. He probably shouldn’t work in service, frankly, but we’re a family business and we all do our bit.”
When the café hit the news last week, with headlines such as “Rhubarb Grumble”, John made a hasty departure and hasn’t been seen at his serving post since. In his absence, the controversy moved seamlessly on to Emma’s “humorous” musings about the Northern character.
The North-South divide remains raw, so why say it? “Well, I’m a Northerner, too,” huffs Emma. “I came here from Manchester. It’s like sending yourself up. One of the things I love most about the North is that you don’t get so much false niceness. People tend to be the way they are, and if they’re not all smiling and asking you if you’re having a nice day, it doesn’t mean they aren’t friendly.
“We’re a little business, trying to get by, and we wouldn’t survive long if we made a habit of being rude. Most of our customers say really nice things about us, and the one who complained about John said they loved everything else about us.”
It isn’t hard to see why. The Temporary Measure, occupying a beamed former pub, is by no means the least friendly café in Britain, but it must be one of the crankiest. Most of the space is filled with a jumble of toys, cards, books, balls of wool and artworks. There are seven small tables at which you can slurp “the best coffee in the universe” and eat scones baked by Emma’s mother, Jackie.
This kind of eccentric outpost of Britain’s depressingly homogenous café culture needs a voice, and Emma is really highlighting the programmed politeness that prevails elsewhere.
The big chains drill their staff into a state of robotic servility. Everyone smiles, asks how you are, hopes you are having a nice day. Starbucks demands to know your first name before serving you a coffee, while Pret A Manger has a totalitarian staff code under which employees are not allowed to be “moody or bad-tempered”.
It isn’t like that at Temporary Measures. Emma and her family came to Keswick seven years ago because they loved the town, and, although they can’t really afford the hefty Main Street rent, they struggle by because they like the buzz of being at the heart of things. They are all in it together. “I raised four children, and they are all lovely,” says Jackie, “and not only that, but lovely in their own ways.”
Their seats are squashy, their cakes crumbly, and their manners all their own. And, as they don’t quite say in the North, if it doesn’t suit you, tough.
